Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The original idea of using a Shared Attention Residual Gaussian Distribution (ARGD) module in the posterior path of a CVAE for gloss-free Sign Language Translation (SLT) is strong, particularly in its attempt to model uncertainty and refine latent representations through attention-driven stochastic perturbations. However, it still assumes a unidirectional flow of textual influence—text adjusts the visual prior via residual attention—and treats modality interaction as asymmetric. Drawing inspiration from Papers 1–3, especially the emphasis on cross-modal alignment (Paper 1), knowledge distillation (Paper 3), and semantic smoothing (Paper 2), I propose a more dynamic and bidirectional framework. My key insight is that instead of treating text as a corrective signal to the visual prior, both modalities should co-evolve through iterative refinement within the latent space, guided by uncertainty-aware attention residuals. This leads to a novel architecture: the **Mutually Refining Variational Autoencoder with Dynamic ARGD Feedback (MR-VAE-DAF)**. Unlike static or one-way integration, this model introduces a recurrent refinement loop where both visual and textual latents are updated alternately using shared ARGD modules that compute *bidirectional* attention residuals, each parametrizing a Gaussian adjustment to the counterpart’s latent distribution. Crucially, the process is governed by an adaptive stopping mechanism based on mutual information convergence, ensuring efficiency without sacrificing alignment quality. Furthermore, I integrate a contrastive semantic regularization derived from LLM-augmented captions (inspired by Paper 2) to stabilize training and improve generalization on rare signs. This approach fundamentally rethinks cross-modal integration in SLT—not as conditioning or correction, but as collaborative inference under uncertainty. It differs from existing methods by introducing symmetry, recurrence, and self-regulated refinement into the VAE framework, addressing KL collapse more effectively while enhancing long-range coherence. The design remains feasible by leveraging lightweight transformers and shared parameters, yet pushes novelty through its dynamic, feedback-based architecture.

