Idea 0 proposes using an ARGD module to adjust the posterior latent code via attention residuals from textual context, shared across sequences, and includes mutual information maximization. This is novel, especially in the context of SLT without glosses, and represents a meaningful advancement in how textual guidance is stochastically integrated into the VAE posterior path.

However, Idea 1 goes substantially further by introducing *bidirectional*, *iterative* latent refinement through dynamic feedback loops between modalities using the same ARGD module. The inclusion of an Adaptive Refinement Scheduler (ARS) based on mutual information convergence and an LLM-based semantic consistency loss adds layers of innovation not seen in any of the provided papers. Crucially, the concept of co-evolving latent codes via stochastic residual updates in both directions—visual-to-text and text-to-visual—represents a paradigm shift from standard asymmetric conditioning in CVAEs. This bidirectional, uncertainty-aware refinement mechanism has no clear precedent in the listed works or common SLT/VAAE literature, making it a stronger candidate for high-impact publication.

While both ideas are well-structured and feasible, **Idea 1** demonstrates greater conceptual novelty due to its dynamic, iterative, and symmetric latent interaction framework, which transcends incremental improvement and proposes a new inference paradigm in multimodal VAEs.

